# Environment Variables Template
# This file documents all available environment variables

# ==========================================
# Google Analytics Configuration
# ==========================================

# Analytics are controlled by environment-specific files:
#   .env.development   → NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_ANALYTICS=false (auto-loaded with npm run dev)
#   .env.production    → NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_ANALYTICS=true  (auto-loaded with npm run build)
#   .env.local         → Overrides both (for local testing only)

# To test analytics in development, add to .env.local:
# NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_ANALYTICS=true

# To use a different Google Analytics ID, add to .env.local:
# NEXT_PUBLIC_GA_MEASUREMENT_ID=G-XXXXXXXXXX

# ==========================================
# AWS Deployment Configuration
# ==========================================
# These are only needed if deploying from your local machine
# GitHub Actions uses OIDC authentication instead

# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# AWS_S3_BUCKET=www.synepho.com
# CLOUDFRONT_DISTRIBUTION_ID=E2UW9JLSX34HRT

# ==========================================
# IMPORTANT NOTES
# ==========================================

# NODE_ENV: Do NOT set this manually!
# Next.js automatically sets NODE_ENV based on the command:
#   - npm run dev    → NODE_ENV=development
#   - npm run build  → NODE_ENV=production
#   - npm run start  → NODE_ENV=production

# Variables with NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix:
#   - Available in both server AND client-side code
#   - Baked into the static build at build time
#   - Use for non-sensitive, public configuration

# Variables without NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix:
#   - Only available server-side (NOT in this static export project)
#   - Use for API keys and sensitive data (in non-static projects)
